    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Its name comes from a Native American word meaning “water eyes,” inspired by the twin lakes that sit like eyes on the town’s edge.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        14,
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wewahitchka%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Wewahitchka sits at the junction of Florida State Roads 71 and 22, right in northeastern Gulf County.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wewahitchka%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "From there, SR 71 leads north 27 miles to Blountstown and south 24 miles to Port St. Joe, while SR 22 heads west 28 miles to Panama City.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        17,
        18
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wewahitchka%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
